-- Project Euler #42: Coded Triangle Numbers
-- A word's value is the sum of its letter positions (A=1, ..., Z=26).
-- A "triangle word" has a value equal to some t_n = n*(n+1)/2.
-- Count the triangle words in a list.
--
-- This demo uses a 15-word inline list (answer: 8).
-- The original problem uses words.txt (1786 words); the full-list answer is 162.

(0 (64 sub plus) fold) 'word-value def

-- precompute triangle numbers up to 60 (covers any 2-3 letter word value)
1 11 range (dup 1 plus mul 2 div) each 'tris let

["SKY" "RUG" "LOG" "A" "AT" "IS" "WE" "IF"
 "HAS" "FOG" "HELLO" "WORLD" "CODE" "MATH" "TEST"]
  (word-value) each
  (tris swap member) filter
  len print
